cs.AR, cs.SY, cs.ARQ, cs.DC, cs.NE 

This paper is likely to belong to the cs.AR (Architecture) sub-category as it deals with the experimental characterization and analysis of latency variation and latency-reliability trade-offs in modern DRAM chips, which is a fundamental aspect of computer architecture. It could also belong to cs.SY (Systems and Control) as it proposes a new mechanism, FLY-DRAM, to improve system performance by exploiting latency variation across DRAM cells. Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.ARQ (Quantum Computing and Information) as it deals with the characteristics of DRAM cells and their operations, which could be relevant to quantum computing. It could also be classified under cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) as it evaluates the performance of FLY-DRAM in a simulated 8-core system. Finally, it could be categorized under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it proposes a new mechanism that uses spatial locality to improve performance, which could be relevant to neural networks and evolutionary algorithms.
